The President of the United States welcomed leaders of the Pacific Islands to Washington for a summit. He emphasized the shared history and relationships between the nations, particularly in the fight for freedom during World War Two. The President highlighted the importance of security in the Pacific and expressed commitment to tackling the climate crisis and rebuilding the global economy post-COVID-19. The United States announced over $110 million in expanded programs to improve the lives of Pacific Islanders, with a focus on climate resilience and sustainable development. Diplomatic steps were also taken, including recognizing the Cook Islands and Niue as sovereign states and negotiating a Compact of Free Association with three partners in the region. The President also addressed Russia's actions in Ukraine, stating that the United States will never recognize Russia's claims on Ukrainian territory. He commended the Pacific Island leaders for their strong moral leadership on global issues. The President concluded by expressing excitement for the summit and dinner at the White House.